Zero Token Protocol v1.0 (Z₀)

Problem

Speech runs faster than thought assembly.

When Δt_thought > Δt_speech, humans insert fillers to:
	•	maintain conversational control
	•	preserve cadence
	•	avoid silence (which risks interruption or loss of authority)

Existing fillers leak meaning:
	•	“um/uh” → hesitation
	•	slang/swears → emotional or identity load
	•	“like/you know” → framing distortion

Result: signal contamination.

⸻

Core Insight

Speech requires a keep-alive signal—not meaning.

So we introduce a true zero token:
	•	preserves time
	•	preserves rhythm
	•	preserves channel
	•	adds no semantic payload

⸻

Definition

Zero Token (Z₀):
A minimal phonetic unit inserted into speech that maintains temporal continuity while introducing ~zero semantic, emotional, or identity load.

⸻

Canonical Form

Primary Token Set (recommended)
	•	“mm” (default anchor)
	•	“eh” (soft continuation)
	•	“na” (light bridge)

These were selected because they:
	•	exist across many languages (low cultural load)
	•	are vowel/consonant minimal (fast deployment)
	•	blend into speech without attention spikes

⸻

Operational Modes

1. Buffer Mode (pure thinking gap)

“I was gonna—mm—go over there…”

	•	Purpose: buy time
	•	Constraint: no tone shift

⸻

2. Bridge Mode (connect fragments)

“So—eh—I think what’s happening is…”

	•	Purpose: maintain flow across incomplete thoughts

⸻

3. Cadence Lock Mode (hold floor)

“Right—mm—so here’s the thing…”

	•	Purpose: prevent interruption while assembling next idea

⸻

System Model

Let:
	•	C = conversational channel
	•	R = rhythm
	•	M = meaning load
	•	E = emotional load

For Z₀:
	•	Maintain: C, R
	•	Constrain:
	•	dM ≈ 0
	•	dE ≈ 0

⸻

Why This Works

Z₀ acts like a heartbeat packet in a network:
	•	keeps connection alive
	•	prevents takeover
	•	allows computation to finish

Without Z₀ → people substitute:
	•	emotion (swearing)
	•	identity (slang)
	•	noise (rambling fillers)

Z₀ = clean buffer instead of corrupted patch

